    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1974-10-24T11:31:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1974-10-24T11:31:00-05:00" n="77"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d77">
                <head>77. Message From Secretary of State <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1" type="from"
                        >Kissinger</persName> to the President’s Deputy Assistant for National
                    Security Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_SBC_1" type="to"
                        >Scowcroft</persName>)<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d77fn1">Source:
                            <persName corresp="#p_FGR_1">Ford</persName> Library, National Security
                        Adviser, Presidential Trip Files, Box 4, November 1974, <gloss
                            target="#t_Hakto_1">Hakto</gloss> (1). Secret; Sensitive; Eyes Only;
                        Immediate. <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1">Kissinger</persName> was in Moscow
                        for meetings with <persName corresp="#p_BLI_1">Brezhnev</persName>,
                            <persName corresp="#p_GAA_1">Gromyko</persName>, and other Soviet
                        officials.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Moscow</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1974-10-24T16:31:00+00:00">October 24, 1974,
                        1631Z</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_Hakto_1">Hakto</gloss> 4. 1. The Department has asked me to
                    send a memo to the White House on the South African question at the <gloss
                        target="#t_UN_1">UN</gloss> (<gloss target="#t_Tosec_1">Tosec</gloss>
                        43).<note n="2" xml:id="d77fn2">Dated October 23. (National Archives, <gloss
                            target="#t_RG_1">RG</gloss> 59, Central Foreign Policy Files,
                        D740303–0048)</note> For obvious reasons, this is a matter best handled
                    orally. I have discussed it with the President and he has agreed with my
                    recommendation that we veto the expulsion of South Africa, if necessary.<note
                        n="3" xml:id="d77fn3">The Security Council debated the issue of South
                        Africa’s expulsion October 18–30. A draft resolution recommending immediate
                        expulsion was not adopted (the United States, United Kingdom, and France
                        voted against the resolution), however, the General Assembly suspended South
                        Africa from the twenty-ninth session on November 12. (<hi rend="italic"
                            >Yearbook of the United Nations, 1974</hi>, pp. 106–117)</note>
                </p>
                <p>2. Warm regards.</p>
            </div>
